RECORD CORRECTION (second agent on this bead). The 14:23 close was premature: the bead was marked closed while its tests were still UNCOMMITTED in the shared working tree, so nothing had actually landed. The tests are now landed in commit 1661dee, and strengthened well past the original version (which asserted only 'final level >= base level' over 5 hardcoded statements).

LANDED (1661dee) — six laws over generated (statement, policy) pairs in crates/oraclemcp-guard/tests/proptest_invariants.rs:
 1. composition never loosens the base verdict — base level carried through unchanged (==, not >=), floor only rises, every predicate attributable to a matched rule;
 2. composition is MONOTONE — splicing extra rules in at any generated position never loosens: a deny can never be reopened, the floor only rises, predicates only accumulate (this is the bead's headline law; the original test did not cover it at all);
 3. rule order carries no authority — rotation-invariant outcome/floor/predicate-set, so there is no first-match/else precedence that could shadow a rule;
 4. an empty policy is the identity, never a grant;
 5. no policy can unlock a Forbidden base — refusal stays attributed to the classifier, not to a rule;
 6. the N3 predicate rewrite cannot launder a statement into a weaker verdict — danger/level never drop, a read-only base stays read-only, and the policy filter must survive into the rendered SQL (SEC-1).

TEETH VERIFIED, NOT ASSUMED: mutating the composer max->min is caught by laws 1+2 with a genuine counterexample (a catch-all read_only floor pulling a DDL drop statement down from DDL clearance to READ_ONLY); reachability probes confirmed the Narrow/Narrow and Reclassified arms are actually exercised, so no law passes vacuously. That counterexample is frozen as the representative adversarial-corpus case policy_composition_corpus_read_only_floor_never_demotes_a_ddl_statement.

